Introduction

This project builds off of project two. So the description and model part of the project will look the same as project two.

Data Description

The data I choose describes the housing prices in Melbourne. I am interested in looking for a relationship between a property sale price and the year built, property size, property type, and suburb. Below the data is being filtered and presented. I am only interested in looking specific suburbs and properties larger that 50 square meters. The data can be looked at in the table below.

# Disabling scientific notation for this chunk. No numbers are that large
options(scipen=999)

#Reading in the data
data <- read.csv("Melbourne_housing_FULL.csv") %>%
  dplyr::select(Regionname, Type, YearBuilt, BuildingArea, Price, 
                Method)

#Dropping rows with incomplete data
data <- na.omit(data)

# Filtering to only look at the properties I am interested in
# Homes above 50 square meters and less than 1500 square meters
data <- data[!(data$BuildingArea<=50 | data$BuildingArea>=1500),]
# Home built only after 1900
data <- data[(data$YearBuilt>=1900),]
# Only homes that have sold
data <- data[(data$Method=='S'),]
# Filtering to only look at two suburbs
data <- data[(data$Regionname=='Northern Metropolitan') | (data$Regionname=='Southern Metropolitan')  ,]

# Renaming categorical variables
data <- data %>% 
  mutate(Type = replace(Type, Type == 'u', 'Apartment'))
data <- data %>% 
  mutate(Type = replace(Type, Type == 't', 'Townhouse'))
data <- data %>% 
  mutate(Type = replace(Type, Type == 'h', 'House'))

#Creating a dummy variable for the housing type and region variables
data <- dummy_cols(data, select_columns = c('Type', 'Regionname'))

#Displaying the data
datatable(data[,1:5], class = 'display')
# Used for summary statistics
data$TypeDummy <- as.numeric(as.factor(data$Type))
data$RegionDummy <- as.numeric(as.factor(data$Regionname))

# Filtering to only look at the suburbs I am interested in
data <- data %>% 
  rename(
     NorthMetro = `Regionname_Northern Metropolitan`,
    SouthMetro = `Regionname_Southern Metropolitan`
    )

#Generating summary statistics for the data
YearBuilt_summ <- data %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(YearBuilt), sd = sd(YearBuilt), median = median(YearBuilt), IQR = IQR(YearBuilt), mode = getmode(YearBuilt), sampeSize = length(YearBuilt))
building_summ <- data %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(BuildingArea), sd = sd(BuildingArea), median = median(BuildingArea),   IQR = IQR(BuildingArea), mode = getmode(BuildingArea), sampeSize = length(BuildingArea))
price_summ <- data %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(Price), sd = sd(Price), median = median(Price),   IQR = IQR(Price), mode = getmode(Price), sampeSize = length(Price))
type_summ <- data %>% 
  summarise(mean = mean(TypeDummy), sd = sd(TypeDummy), median = median(TypeDummy),   IQR = IQR(TypeDummy), mode = getmode(TypeDummy), sampeSize = length(TypeDummy))
region_summ <- data %>% 
  summarise(mean = mean(RegionDummy), sd = sd(RegionDummy), median = median(RegionDummy),   IQR = IQR(RegionDummy), mode = getmode(RegionDummy), sampeSize = length(RegionDummy))

#Neatly displaying the summary statistics
cols <- c('Housing Type', 'YearBuilt', 'Building Size', 'Region', 'Price')
col.Variable <- data.frame(cols)
summ1 <- rbind(type_summ, YearBuilt_summ, building_summ, region_summ, price_summ)
summ <- cbind2(col.Variable, summ1)
knitr::kable(summ, align='lccrr', caption = 'Mean, Standard Deviation, Median, and IQR of the data', col.names = c('Variable', 'Mean', 'Standard Deviation', 'Median', 'IQR', 'Mode', 'Sample Size'))

Regression Models

Now lets create a regression model that includes the interactions, and one that does not. Note that apartments and south metro are the reference groups for the two categorical predictors.

model <- lm(Price ~ YearBuilt+BuildingArea+Type_Townhouse+Type_House+NorthMetro+NorthMetro:Type_Townhouse+NorthMetro:Type_House, data=data)
coef <- coefficients(model)
anova <- anova(model)
summary <- summary(model)
ci <- as_tibble(confint(model, level=0.95))
t <- as_tibble(summary[[4]])
# Reduced
model_red <- lm(Price ~ YearBuilt+BuildingArea+Type_Townhouse+Type_House+NorthMetro, data=data)
coef_red <- coefficients(model_red)
anova_red <- anova(model_red)
summary_red <- summary(model_red)
ci_red <- as_tibble(confint(model_red, level=0.95))
t_red <- as_tibble(summary_red[[4]])

col.Variable2 <- data.frame(Variable)
summ3 <- cbind2(col.Variable2, t)

The full regression model is \[ \hat{Y} = 10911432.15 -5346X_{\mbox{YearBuilt}} + 4148.61X_{\mbox{HomeSize}} + 265131.89X_{\mbox{Townhouse}} \\ + 596166.09X_{\mbox{House}} -54264.76X_{\mbox{NorthMetro}} -158852.92X_{\mbox{NorthMetro:Townhouse}} \\ -642515.76X_{\mbox{NorthMetro:House}} \]

The reduced regression model is \[ \hat{Y} = 10911432.15 -5346X_{\mbox{YearBuilt}} + 4148.61X_{\mbox{HomeSize}} + 265131.89X_{\mbox{Townhouse}} \\ + 596166.09X_{\mbox{House}} -54264.76X_{\mbox{NorthMetro}} \]

AIC

Now lets look at the AIC values for each model. For the full model we have 98819.8827988, and for the reduced we have 99087.9284743. The lower the value, the better. This shows that the full model is preferred. This result does agree with what I found in project two.

Adjusted \(R^2\)

Full: \(R_{adj}^2=0.59\); that is, approximately 59% of the variance in home sale price is explained by the current model.

Reduced: \(R_{adj}^2=0.56\); that is, approximately 56% of the variance in home sale price is explained by the reduced model.

The \(R_{adj}^2\) value is higher for the full model, meaning that more of the variance is explained by the full model. This result also agrees with what was found in project two.

Model Analysis

Now lets do some analysis on the full model, which was determined to be the best model.

Check for Outliers and Influence/Leverage Points

# Studentized deleted residuals
data$res <- studres(model)
# Create Flag Variable
data$res_flag <- if_else(abs(data$res)>=3, 1, 0)
# Count the number with an issue
res_count <- table(data$res_flag)
# Filter the results we're concerned about
data_filtered <- filter(data, res_flag==0)

From the studentized residuals, we have 66 outliers. These can be seen in the plot below, where the ends of the distribution pass 3.

# Plot to visualize residuals
ggplot(data=data, aes(x=data$res)) +
    geom_density(alpha=.3, fill='#69b3a2') +
    theme_ipsum() +
    xlab('Residual') + 
    ylab('Density') +
    scale_fill_brewer(palette="Set1")

Now lets also look at a Cook’s plot. This will help to see observations that can have influence/leverage on our model and should be investigated. The second plot is just a zoomed in version of the first one, to help see the total observations of interest.

# Cooks plot
gg_cooksd(model, label = FALSE, show.threshold = FALSE) + theme_ipsum()

gg_cooksd(model, label = FALSE, show.threshold = FALSE) + theme_ipsum() + ylim(0.0, 0.05)

I removed the labels from the Cook’s plot because they were cluttering the plot. Next lets see what the model looks like without these influence points.

Sensitivity Analysis

Check for Multicollinearity

Now lets look for multicollinearity between the two continuous predictors.

ggplot(data=data, aes(x=data$YearBuilt, y=data$BuildingArea)) +
    geom_point(alpha=.3, color = "#69b3a2") +
    theme_ipsum_es() +
    xlab('Year Built') + 
    ylab('Home Size')

viff <- vif(model)
# Vif, try removing the categorical variables and check vif
viff_red <- vif(lm(Price ~ YearBuilt+BuildingArea, data=data))

Using VIF, the two continuous predictors have values of 1.3396583 and 1.3498394. With removing the categorical predictors from the model, I get VIF values of 1.006864 and 1.006864. Both set of values are acceptable. A good VIF value is usually in the range of \((1,2)\). This also agrees with the plot as it does not show a linear relationship between the two. This means we should not remove one of those predictors from the model.

    scale_color_brewer(name = "Price", palette="Paired")

It might not look like much changed, but the gaps between lines has actually increased. This means that there is more of a difference in the price between the housing type and region.

The final plots below show the error between the actual prices and the predicted prices. If a predicted price is the same as the actual price, the point should lay perfectly on a \(y=x\) line, and the error between the two will be zero. The filtered model that does not have the influence points is not only clustered more around the \(y=x\) line, but also has a smaller error range overall. So I would say that removing the influence points have improved the model overall.

#Plot fitted values vs known values.
get_err <- lm(model$fitted.values ~ data$Price)

ggplot(data=data, aes(x=data$Price, y=model$fitted.values, color=get_err$residuals)) +
    geom_jitter(alpha=.5) +
    geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1) +
    theme_ipsum() +
    xlab('Known Values') + 
    ylab('Fitted Values') +
    scale_color_gradient(low = "yellow", high = "blue", na.value = NA) + 
    guides(color=guide_legend(title="Error"))
